    "abstractNote": "The two chief sources for the legend of Abgar in the various forms it adopted in the period up to AD 384, to which this paper is confined, are Eusebius' <i>History of the Church</i> and the <i>Peregrinatio Egeriae</i>. These are discussed in reverse order, because an examination of Eusebius leads naturally into the most speculative part: the investigation into the origins of the legend. Here the person of the historical king Abgar the Great comes into view and a third text, the description of the flood of 201 from the Chronicle of Edessa is presented as a neglected witness to the religious allegiance of this man. For the references, see the separate file containing the bibliography of the whole volume.",
